The Matrix Model Free Energy 

Let us now consider the matrix integral we considered before, but with all flavors
massive. In this case, we can reinterpret the -function as arising from the
change of variables
DQDQ  =  D M DQDQ (QQ -M)
Thus, to find the effective superpotential as a function of the glueball superfield
(), we must supplement the results of the previous section with a mass term
for the remaining mesons and then compute the integral over  as well.
We recall that we are interested only in the 1-boundary free energy. Thus, the
integral can be computed by a saddle-point approximation. Alternatively, it is easy to see
that the one-boundary free energy is given by the sum of all tree-level Feynman
diagrams arising from the superpotential (). This implies that,
as expected, the effective superpotential is unique even when expressed in terms of
the glueball superfield. The vacua of the theory arise in this language as the critical
points of .

We now illustrate this simple observation for the  theory with three flavors,
leaving to the reader the exercise of recovering the more involved results of
section .


